5. Data Visualization

This chapter introduces basic R plotting using the ggplot2 package. ggplot2 is a contributed package written by Hadley Wickham, which is an implementation of the Grammar of Gaphics by Leland Wilkinson. One can install ggplot2 via install.packages("ggplot2"). The ggplot2 package offers a wide variety of powerful tools for creating plots of publication quality. It is impossible to go over every single detail about these facilities in a short time frame. This note aims to help one get started, and so only highlights the most important features of ggplot2 and introduces some basic fundamentals of plotting using it.

Good references for using ggplot2 include:

  1. ggplot2 website for official documentation.
  2. Hadley Wickhams ggplot2: Elegant Graphics for Data Analysis for more comprehensive introduction.
  3. RStudios ggplot2 cheat sheet for getting started quickly.

This chapter focuses on two most frequently used plotting functions in ggplot2: qplot() and ggplot().

5.1 qplot()

The qplot() function is very similar to the basic plot() function from the R base package but with many (nice if you like them) built-in features. It can be used to create and combine easily different types of plots.

To plot using qplot(), the following inputs are necessary:

  1. data: must be in the form of data.frame1.
  2. geoms: lines, points, bars, etc.
  3. aesthetics: color, size, shape, position, etc.

The following examples illustrate how to plot using qplot():

# simulate a data frame
set.seed(1)
Y <- rchisq(250, 2)*1000 + 1000
C <- pmax(rnorm(250, 0, 2)*250 + 0.5*Y + 1500, 0)
G <- 0
data1 <- cbind(G, Y, C)
Y <- rchisq(250, 3)*1000 + 1500
C <- pmax(rnorm(250, 0, 3)*250 + 0.7*Y + 1200, 0)
G <- 1
data2 <- cbind(G, Y, C)
data <- rbind(data1, data2)
Data <- data.frame(data)
attach(Data)  
Data$G <- factor(Data$G, levels = c(0, 1), labels = c("female", "male")) 
S <- rbinom(500, 1, 0.5)
Data <- cbind(Data, S)
Data$S <- factor(Data$S, levels = c(0, 1), labels = c("NC", "TX")) 
names(Data) <- c("Gender", "Income", "Consumption", "State")

# scatterplot using qplot()
library(ggplot2)
qplot(log(Income), log(Consumption),        # specify variables for the x axis and y axis
      data = Data,                          # input data 
      geom = c("point"),                    # specify geoms, default for two variables is scatter plot (points) 
      color = Gender, shape = Gender)       # add color and shape aesthetics according to the "drv" variable

The facets argument enables one to split up the data by one or more variables and plot the subsets of data together.

qplot(log(Consumption), data = Data,        # default for one variable is histogram
      fill = Gender, bins = 50,             # fill histograms with different colors according to "drv"
      facets = Gender ~. )                  # facets (conditional plots), row ~ column, panels according to "drv"

qplot() allows multiple geoms in the same plot.

qplot(log(Income), log(Consumption), 
      data = Data[Data$Gender == "male",],         
      geom = c("smooth", "point"),        # add more geoms
      method = "lm")                      # change method for "smooth" geom, default "loess" -> linear regression

One can also add a title to the plot and customize the axis labels.

qplot(log(Income), data = Data, 
      geom = "density",                          # geom = kernel density 
      fill = Gender,
      linetype = Gender,
      facets = Gender ~ State ,
      main = "Empirical Density of Log Income",  # add title 
      xlab = "Log Income",                       # change labels of x axis and y axis
      ylab = "Density")

qplot() is a convenient plotting tool which can do adequately good job quickly in most circumstances, but ggplot() is the core function of ggplot2 and is much more flexible (and so capable) than qplot().

5.2 ggplot()

Plots are built layer-by-layer using ggplot(). A general plotting procedure includes the following steps:

  1. Input data: must be a data frame.
  2. Set up aesthetic mappings: describe how variables in the data are mapped to aesthetics of geoms.
  3. Add geoms: geometric objects include point (geom_point()), line (geom_line()), histogram (geom_histogram()), etc. Each geom function has its own options for aesthetics.
  4. Define facets (facet_grid()): a matrix of panels defined by row and column faceting variables.
  5. Lay out statistics (stat_function()): statistical transformations like fitted line, quantile, density. etc.
  6. Modify global setttings (theme()): legend, backgrounds, fonts, etc.
  7. Annotate the plot: add small annotations (e.g., text labels, comment) using labs(), annotate(), etc.

Lets first prepare the data that will be used in plotting and then illustrate how to implement ggplot().

library(readr)
library(dplyr)
setwd("/Users/ouyangfu/Dropbox/Teaching/financial econometrics/2018/data") # set working directory (Mac OS) 
sp500m <- read_csv("sp500month.csv")  %>%                                  # read S&P500 monthly data 
          select(Date, `Adj Close`) %>%                                    # keep only "date" and "adj close" 
          rename(index = `Adj Close`)                                      # rename "adj close" -> "price"
sp500m <- arrange(sp500m, Date)                                            # sort data according to "date"
sp500m <- filter(sp500m, Date >= as.Date("1990-01-01"))                    # keep only post-1990 data
sp500d <- read_csv("sp500day.csv") %>%
          select(Date, `Adj Close`) %>%
          rename(index = `Adj Close`)
sp500d$Date <- as.Date(strptime(as.character(sp500d$Date), "%m/%d/%Y"))    # change the date-time format
sp500d <- arrange(sp500d, Date)
sp500d <- filter(sp500d, Date >= as.Date("1990-01-01"))
vix <- read_csv("vix.csv") %>%
       select(Date, `Adj Close`) %>%
       rename(vix = `Adj Close`)
vix <- arrange(vix, Date)
vix <- filter(vix, Date >= as.Date("1990-01-01"))
dailyData <- inner_join(sp500d, vix, by = "Date")                          # merge sp500d and vix data by "date"
dailyData <- mutate(dailyData,                                             # create new variables
                    lvix = lag(vix, n = 1L),                               # lagged vix
                    lindex = lag(index, n = 1L),                           # lagged S&P500 index
                    Dvix = vix - lvix,                                     # changes in vix                                 
                    logRindex = log(index/lindex))                         # log returns of S&P500 index
sp500m <- mutate(sp500m,
                 lindex = lag(index, n = 1L),
                 logRindex = log(index/lindex),
                 Window = Date >= as.Date("2002-07-01")) 
sp500m$Window <- factor(sp500m$Window, levels = c(FALSE, TRUE), 
                        labels = c("Before 7/1/2002", "After 7/1/2002"))
scatterplot <- ggplot(subset(dailyData, Date >= as.Date("2015-01-01")),    # set up ggplot with data and aes
                      aes(logRindex*100, Dvix)) + 
  geom_point(alpha = .75, size = 2, color = "cyan4") +                     # add "point" geom and modify it 
  labs(title = "S&P 500 Log Returns vs Changes of VIX, 2015",              # add title and axis labels 
       x = "S&P 500 Log Returns", y = "Changes of VIX") + 
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", level = 0.9, color = "violetred3") +          # add "line" geom and modify it        
  theme(axis.title = element_text(family = "serif"),
        plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5, family = "serif", 
                                  face = "bold"))                          # modify theme characteristics
print(scatterplot)

One can add \(\LaTeX\) elements to the plot using the TeX() function in the latex2exp package.

library(latex2exp)
g <- ggplot(sp500m, aes(Date))                                      
g + 
  geom_line(aes(y = index, color = Window), size = 0.5) +           
  theme_bw(base_family = "serif") +                             # change theme background and font
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5,  
                                  face = "bold")) +             # modify theme characteristics
  facet_grid(. ~ Window) +                                      # add panels, see facet_wrap() also
  labs(title = TeX("Themes, Facets and $\\LaTeX$")) +           # add title  
  labs(y = "S&P 500 Index", x = TeX("Date ($\\tau$)"))          # customize labels

One can easily arrange multiple ggplots on the same page using the ggarrange() function in the ggpubr package2.

histogram1 <- ggplot(dailyData, aes(logRindex)) + 
  geom_histogram(aes(y = ..density..), bins = 100, color="white", 
                 fill="dodgerblue3", 
                alpha = 0.75, size = 0.1) + 
  stat_function(fun = dnorm, color = "darkred", size = 0.5,     # add stats: theoretical pdf
                args = list(mean = mean(dailyData$logRindex, 
                                        na.rm = T), 
                            sd = sd(dailyData$logRindex, 
                                    na.rm = T))) +
  labs(title = "Histogram and Kernel Density of Daily Data", 
       x = "Daily Data", y = "Density") +
  theme(axis.title = element_text(family = "serif", size = 9),
        plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5, family = "serif", 
                                  size = 11))
histogram2 <- ggplot(sp500m, aes(logRindex)) +
  geom_histogram(aes(y = ..density..), bins = 80, color="white", 
                 fill="seagreen4", 
                 alpha = 0.75, size = 0.1) + 
  stat_function(fun = dnorm, color = "darkred", size = 0.5,
                args = list(mean = mean(sp500m$logRindex, 
                                        na.rm = T), 
                            sd = sd(sp500m$logRindex, 
                                    na.rm = T))) +
  labs(title = "Histogram and Kernel Density of Monthly Data", 
       x = "Monthly Data", y = "Density") +
  theme(axis.title = element_text(family = "serif", size = 9),
        plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5, family = "serif", 
                                  size = 11))
y <- quantile(dailyData$logRindex, c(0.25, 0.75), na.rm = T) 
x <- qnorm(c(0.25, 0.75))         
slope <- diff(y)/diff(x)             
int <- y[1] - slope*x[1] 
QQ1 <- ggplot(dailyData, aes(sample = logRindex)) +
  geom_qq(alpha = 0.5, size = 1, color = "dodgerblue3") +
  geom_abline(intercept=int, slope=slope, color = "darkred", size = 1/2) +
  labs(title = "Q-Q Plot of Daily Data", 
       x = "Normal Quantile", y = "Quantile of Daily Data") +
  theme(axis.title = element_text(family = "serif", size = 9),
        plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5, family = "serif", 
                                  size = 11))
y <- quantile(sp500m$logRindex, c(0.25, 0.75), na.rm = T) 
x <- qnorm(c(0.25, 0.75))         
slope <- diff(y)/diff(x)             
int <- y[1] - slope*x[1] 
QQ2 <- ggplot(sp500m, aes(sample = logRindex)) +
  geom_qq(alpha = 0.5, size = 1, color = "seagreen4") +
  geom_abline(intercept=int, slope=slope, color = "darkred", size = 1/2) +
  labs(title = "Q-Q Plot of Monthly Data", 
       x = "Normal Quantile", y = "Quantile of Monthly Data") +
  theme(axis.title = element_text(family = "serif", size = 9),
        plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5, family = "serif", 
                                  size = 11))
library(ggpubr)
figMatrix <- ggarrange(histogram1, histogram2, QQ1, QQ2,
                       labels = c("A", "B", "C","D"),
                       ncol = 2, nrow = 2)
annotate_figure(figMatrix,
                top = text_grob("Empirical Distribution of S&P 500 Log Return", 
                                face = "bold", size = 12, 
                                family = "serif"))

The following example shows how to add legend, highlight points and add texts in a ggplot.

fig <- ggplot(subset(dailyData, Date >= as.Date("2000-01-01")), 
                aes(Date)) + 
  geom_line(aes(y = vix, color = "VIX"), size = 0.3) +
  geom_line(aes(y = index/50, color = "S&P 500"), size = 0.3) +
  geom_point(y = max(dailyData$vix), 
             aes(dailyData$Date[max(dailyData$vix) == dailyData$vix]), 
             colour = "purple", size = 2, shape = 5) +
  annotate("text", family = "serif",
           x = as.Date("2010-06-01"), 
           y = max(dailyData$vix), label = "Peak of VIX") +
  labs(title = "S&P 500 Index and VIX, 2000-2015", 
       x = "Dates", y = "VIX (left) and S&P 500 Index (right)") +        
  theme(axis.title = element_text(family = "serif"),
        plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5, family = "serif",
                                  face = "bold"),
        legend.position = c(0.1, 0.8),
        legend.title = element_blank(),
        legend.background = element_rect(fill=alpha("grey", 0), 
                                         color = "grey", size = 0.8, 
                                         linetype="solid"),
        legend.text = element_text(family = "serif", face = "bold"),
        legend.key = element_rect(color = "transparent")) +
  scale_y_continuous(sec.axis = sec_axis(~.*50))
print(fig)

  1. If factors are used to indicate subsets of the data, they should be properly labeled for being used in qplot().

  2. ggpubr provides many other easy-to-use functions for creating and customizing ggplot2-based publication ready plots.
